{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478130"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:09:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:09:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16978"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16978"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.42,0.02,0.53,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9668"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68113"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9668"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16978"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53570"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3285"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11473"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22795"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39063"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44228"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68113"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent for assessment of escalating behavioural concerns. Over the past year, he has become increasingly defiant at home and school, frequently arguing with teachers and refusing to follow rules. He has been suspended twice for fighting after becoming angry when challenged. His parent notes he has been stealing small items from shops and staying out past curfew despite consequences. He lives with his parent who has a history of depression and substance use. His biological father is incarcerated. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. He is appropriately dressed but avoids eye contact. When discussing his behaviour, he becomes defensive, stating \u0027everyone is always against me\u0027 and that the other students \u0027started it\u0027. He shows little concern when told how his actions affect others. His parent appears overwhelmed and tearful during the consultation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Autism spectrum disorder","Oppositional defiant disorder","Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder","Conduct disorder","Adjustment disorder"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a diagnostic challenge between conduct disorder and oppositional defiant disorder, both of which can present with defiant behaviour and poor emotional regulation. However, several features point more strongly toward conduct disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConduct disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by a pattern of behaviour that violates the basic rights of others or major age-appropriate societal norms. While this patient shows features that overlap with oppositional defiant disorder (arguing, defiance), the presence of premeditated stealing and physical aggression, along with the lack of concern for others, are more consistent with conduct disorder. The family history of parental mental illness and incarceration represents significant environmental risk factors for conduct disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOppositional defiant disorder\u003C/strong\u003E typically involves argumentative and defiant behaviour, particularly toward authority figures. While this patient shows these features, oppositional defiant disorder usually does not include the calculated violation of others\u0027 rights (such as stealing) or the degree of physical aggression seen here. Children with oppositional defiant disorder often show emotional dysregulation but retain some capacity for remorse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAttention deficit hyperactivity disorder\u003C/strong\u003E may present with behavioural difficulties, but these are typically impulsive rather than calculated. While ADHD can co-exist with conduct disorder, the premeditated nature of the stealing and lack of empathy are not typical ADHD features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdjustment disorder\u003C/strong\u003E involves emotional or behavioural symptoms in response to an identifiable stressor. While family dysfunction could be considered a stressor, the pattern and severity of antisocial behaviour exceeds what would be expected in adjustment disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutism spectrum disorder\u003C/strong\u003E can present with social difficulties and behavioural problems, but these typically stem from difficulties with social communication and sensory processing rather than intentional violation of social norms. The presence of calculated antisocial behaviour would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe contribution of adverse family circumstances, including parental mental illness and paternal incarceration, likely plays a significant role in the development of this behaviour pattern. Early intervention, family support, and multidisciplinary management are crucial for improving outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Conduct disorder is characterised by persistent violation of social norms and rights of others, often with lack of remorse and calculated aggression.","Family dysfunction and parental mental illness are significant risk factors for both conduct disorder and oppositional defiant disorder.","The presence of premeditated aggression and violation of others\u0027 rights distinguishes conduct disorder from oppositional defiant disorder."],"references":["American Psychiatric Association DS, American Psychiatric Association DS. Diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders: DSM-5. Washington, DC: American psychiatric association; 2013 May 22."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53570"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16978"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53570"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T10:08:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T10:12:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9668"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68113"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"descrip